  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Mary P. Rogers thanks Maria Weston Chapman for her interest in the anti-slavery activities in Concord, where they are planning an anti-slavery fair in which &quot;we are altogether new hands.&quot; So far &quot;the differences which have been disturbing the brethren&quot; have never been manifested in the female society. However, &quot;now that our Baptist ministers openly oppose the Herald, doubtless many will be carried away by their influence.&quot; She remarks on her husband&apos;s situation and his need for sympathy in the cause. [Mary P. Roger&apos;s husband is Nathaniel Peabody Rogers.] She also mentions Mary Clark.</subfield>
